b'Dining services'
b'UIC may be a diverse campus, but all students have one thing in common: the need for food. Dining Services has caf\xc3\xa9s, cafeterias and fast-food restaurants, including Argo Tea, Au Bon Pain, Chick-fil-A, Dunkin\xe2\x80\x99 Donuts/Baskin-Robbins, Freshii, Moe\xe2\x80\x99s, Panda Express, Port Center Caf\xc3\xa9, Sbarro, Subway, Tropical Smoothie and more.'
b'Dining Services '
b'\xc2\xa0'
b'Disability Resource Center'
b'The Disability Resource Center offers activities, services and resources for students with disabilities and guidance for faculty on accessible teaching.\n1190 Student Services Building\nVoice: 312-413-2183\nVideo Phone: 773-649-4535'
b'Disability Resource Center'
b'Health & Wellness'
b'Don\xe2\x80\x99t fret over a fever. CampusCare, a student health plan paid by student fees, includes services at these clinics:'
b'CampusCare'
b' Counseling Center'
b'Wellness Center'
b''
b'Housing'
b'On-campus: UIC has nine residence halls offering a variety of arrangements, including living learning communities, and options for graduate students, and even temporary guest housing.'
b'residence halls'
b'Housing residents have access to programming, tutoring, interactions with faculty, and connections to other students and campus resources in addition to the convenience of living on campus.'
b'A new academic and residential complex on Harrison street, which will include both academic and residential facilities, is scheduled to open Fall 2019.'
b'\xc2\xa0'
b'ID Center '
b'ID Center '
b'312-413-5940, 1790 Student Services Building; satellite center, 241 Student Center West'
b''
b'Job Services'
b'College life can be expensive. The Student Employment Office helps students find part-time jobs on and off campus to help ease the expenses.\n2100 Student Services Building\n312-996-3130'
b'Student Employment Office'
b'Office of Career Services helps students prepare for careers and find jobs.\n3050 Student Services Building\n312-996-2300'
b'Office of Career Services'
b'\xc2\xa0'
b'Library\n'
b'Library'
b'There are two libraries on the Chicago campus \xe2\x80\x94 the Daley Library on the east side of campus and the\xc2\xa0Library of the Health Sciences on the west side \xe2\x80\x94 and libraries at the health sciences campuses in Peoria, Rockford and Urbana. Get help from librarians face-to-face or through live chat.'
b'IDEA Commons:\nCheck out this popular learning and collaboration space on the first floor of the Daley Library, with meeting spaces, a per\xc2\xadformance area, moveable furniture and more than 100 computers, as well as the Instructional Technology Lab/Student Media Lab.'
b'\xc2\xa0'
b'Maps'
b'Grab an old-school paper map at Building Management in Student Centers East and West, or the Information and Service Center in the Student Services Building. Trying to save paper? Check out the online map.'
b'online map.'
b'\xc2\xa0'
b'Office of the Dean of Students '
b'The Office of the Dean of Students is a resource for advocacy, engagement, support services and other opportunities available on campus. Their mission is to create a student-centered learning environment where students can achieve personal and academic success.\n3030 Student Services Building, 1200 W. Harrison St.'
b'Office of the Dean of Students'
b'\xc2\xa0'
b'Recreation\n'
b'Recreation'
b'Zumba, swimming, massage therapy, and more! UIC has recreation facilities on the east and west sides of campus that offer everything from intramural sports to personal training, as well as an outdoor field complex and outdoor recreation courts for tennis, sand volleyball, basketball and jogging.'
b'Student Recreation Facility\n312-413-5150'
b'Sport and Fitness Center\n312-413-5260'
b'\xc2\xa0'
